<br>
In EQ, when you typed /petition at minimum you got an answer most of the time.  You might not like the answer you got, but you'd get an answer.  If you asked the &quot;guide&quot;:  &quot;Please escalate this to a paid Verrant GM &amp; have them contact me directly&quot;, they did most of the time.  <br>
<br>
In AO, your petition will only be answered if you are persistant and re-petition every 30 minutes.  Then, only if you are lucky.  In AO, if you ask for esacalation, you'll be told (like I was) &quot;they'll just tell you the same thing I am&quot;.  <br>
<br>
In EQ, *if* you lost money/items to a bug or zone crash, you had a chance of getting re-imbursed.  It was a small chance, but a chance none the less.<br>
<br>
In AO, if you lose money/items to a bug or zone crash, you are out of luck.<br>
<br>
Verrant pre-announced *most* patch days, Funcom pre-announces very few.<br>
<br>
I enjoy the game play in AO, but frankly, their version of customer service is pathetic.  I played EQ from beta 2 thru the release of AO.  By the time AO came out, I was pretty bored with EQ.  Like 99% of Norrath, I avoided Verrant GM's like the plague also.<br>
<br>
