<br>
I voted &quot;No, VI does a better job&quot; for one simple reason -- not because I think Verant was any great shakes at public relations or because I miss playing EQ.  I don't.  I haven't touched my EQ account since the day AO went public (except for 5 minutes once to make some enchanter spells for a friend :-) ).  That simple reason is because Verant did what they said they would do -- we may not always have agreed with their decisions, but they started out on Day One saying they would proactively prosecute exploiters.  They did that.  They said they would proactively chase down and ban (if required) grief players.  I personally saw that happen more than once.  What's more, the times I petitioned in EQ, be it to report exploiters or ask for help, I *always* got help.  Right after release my body was stuck in the tunnels under Highpass for 3 days, but eventually I did get a guide who not only retrieved my body but then summoned my puny 10th level butt out of the place :-)  The petitions after that were always answered within an hour or so.<br>
<br>
To date, I have not seen Funcom do diddly against exploiters except nerf one of the main combat classes in the game -- a solution that I don't think was the best available in a game where there is NO faction and the insurance terminals can remove all risks to the players.  Their approach to exploiters is to talk sternly in public and then slap them on the wrist.  That will not end exploiting. I have yet to have one single petition answered.<br>
<br>
I worked for a time on the Sony board as a sysop and I got to deal directly with McQuaid, Geoff Z., Brian Hooks and the lot.  They may come across as arrogant idiots to the general player population but they weren't, they just had some strange ideas about how to deal with the player community.  I eventually quit that position over a situation where their lack of communicative skills left me as a scapegoat, but the fault lies in their methods, not their willingness or their intent.<br>
<br>
I see Funcom enduring some of the same faltering mistakes in the early going.  The player community requires firm leadership from the game designers and it requires absolute honesty, but most of all it requires communication.  Without that, the whole thing is going to collapse on its face.  I'm waiting to see if things improve.  If nothing else, at least Funcom keeps us informed on server status -- one thing it took Verant 2 years to figure out had any value.<br>
<br>
Sinda<br>
